---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Synth1 from "./_Synth1.astro";
import Synth2 from "./_Synth2.astro";
import Synth3 from "./_Synth3.astro";
import Synth4 from "./_Synth4.astro";
import Synth5 from "./_Synth5.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Notes – Novation Peak Sound Design Practice Ladder"
  description="Grounded sound-design exercises using classic synth archetypes"
>
  <!-- article: a self-contained knowledge object (a page you could cite or export as-is) -->
  <article id="practice-ladder">
    <!-- header: the introduction block for the page (title + framing) -->
    <header>
      <!-- h1: name of the page-level object; treat as a title, not a sentence -->
      <h1>Novation Peak – Sound Design Practice Ladder</h1>

      <!-- p: the default unit of explanation; keep one idea per paragraph -->
      <p class="subtitle">
        A sequence of "patch archetypes" designed to build control before
        complexity. Each patch is a small study: do it fast once, then repeat
        until it becomes boringly dependable.
      </p>

      <aside
        class="provenance-note"
        role="note"
        aria-label="Authorship and provenance note"
      >
        <span class="provenance-label">AI-generated text</span>
        <span class="provenance-text"
          >Drafted with an AI system. Reviewed and edited by a human.</span
        >
      </aside>
    </header>

    <p>
      The intent is not to collect presets, but to build a mental model: how
      oscillators, envelopes, filters, and modulation interact, and how little
      you can use while still making something expressive. If you want a
      constraint: avoid effects until the patch itself feels alive.
    </p>

    <!-- nav: conceptual navigation; here it's an index into the ladder -->
    <nav aria-label="Practice Ladder Index">
      <!-- ol: use when order matters (a ladder has a recommended sequence) -->
      <ol>
        <li>
          <a href="#single-oscillator-saw-lead">Single-Oscillator Saw Lead</a>
        </li>
        <li><a href="#square-bass-with-snap">Square Bass With Snap</a></li>
        <li><a href="#two-saw-poly-pad">Two-Saw Poly Pad</a></li>
        <li><a href="#pwm-pad-strings">PWM Pad / Strings</a></li>
        <li><a href="#hard-sync-lead">Hard-Sync Lead</a></li>
        <li><a href="#poly-brass-stab">Poly Brass Stab</a></li>
        <li><a href="#fm-bell-electric-piano">FM Bell / Electric Piano</a></li>
        <li><a href="#acid-bassline">Acid Bassline</a></li>
        <li><a href="#string-ensemble">String Ensemble</a></li>
        <li><a href="#evolving-cinematic-pad">Evolving Cinematic Pad</a></li>
      </ol>
    </nav>

    <!-- section: a major thematic grouping; keep headings shallow (h1–h3) -->
    <section id="synthesis">
      <!-- h2: stable category label -->
      <h2>Synthesis</h2>

      <Synth1 />
      <Synth2 />
      <Synth3 />
      <Synth4 />
      <Synth5 />
    </section>

    <!-- footer: closing material for the article -->
    <footer>
      <p class="text-muted">
        This ladder is meant to stay editable. Add variants freely, but try to
        preserve the basic format: a clear goal, a small set of controls, and a
        few tests for whether it worked.
      </p>

      <nav aria-label="Related pages">
        <p class="text-muted">See also:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <a href="/ai-generated/beat-learn">Beat Practice Ladder</a> — the rhythm
            counterpart to this synth ladder
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href="/ai-generated/sheev/">GoatTracker2 on macOS</a> — another angle
            on music tools
          </li>
        </ul>
      </nav>
    </footer>
  </article>
</Layout>
